{
  "answer": "**The couplet closest to your description appears in Ghalib's *Diwan-e-Ghalib*, ghazal 145:**\n\n> Seek not a lesson in a mirage you can't retrace,[^1]  \n> I am but road-dust, aimless is my winding pace, my.[^1]\n\nThis sh'er (couplet) pairs a \"lesson\" (which cannot be retraced, evoking life's elusive teachings) with the poet's self-description as \"road-dust\" (ghubaar-e-raah). No exact phrasing like \"life's lesson\" equated directly to \"dust of the road\" occurs in the English translations of the *Diwan*, despite extensive searches for those terms and their variants across the 239 chapters. Other couplets mention \"lesson\" (e.g., lessons from love's pain or the flower's doom) but lack the road/dust imagery together.[^2][^3][^4]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 145, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/145-na-hoga-yak-biyabaan-maandagi-se-zauq-kam-mera/translation/#p-26d938).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 10, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/10-arz-e-naaz-e-shokhi-e-dandaan-baraaye-khanda-hai/translation/#p-494438).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 22, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/22-chahiye-achhon-ko-jitna-chahiye/translation/#p-b327f3).\n[^4]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 99, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/99-juz-qais-aur-koi-na-aaya-ba-ru-e-kaar/translation/#p-2dd0ef).",
